139
00:09:32,390 --> 00:09:32,950
It's nominal.

140
00:09:33,799 --> 00:09:40,080
But if the status statute uses ambiguous
language, if it reference a contested

141
00:09:40,120 --> 00:09:44,400
prior ruling, or if the change applies to
a jurisdiction with complex carve-outs,

142
00:09:44,760 --> 00:09:48,610
the system flagged is for human
review before any rule is extracted.

143
00:09:48,920 --> 00:09:51,030
The ambiguity is surfaced, not suppressed.

144
00:09:51,530 --> 00:09:56,830
Once a regulatory change has been ingested
and classified, the next agent encodes

145
00:09:57,320 --> 00:10:02,830
it into what we call domain specific
language The DSL is the strategic

146
00:10:02,860 --> 00:10:04,830
center of the enterprise architecture.

147
00:10:05,100 --> 00:10:05,840
Let me explain why.

148
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:07,980
Natural language is ambiguous.

149
00:10:08,280 --> 00:10:10,070
Code is implementation-specific.

150
00:10:10,080 --> 00:10:14,320
It is written in Java or Python or
TypeScript, and it is coupled to

151
00:10:14,320 --> 00:10:15,820
a particular system architecture.

152
00:10:16,580 --> 00:10:19,380
The DSL sits between these two worlds.

153
00:10:20,300 --> 00:10:24,390
It captures the full logical structure
to a tax rule, the condition, the

154
00:10:24,890 --> 00:10:26,910
thresholds, the applicable rates, the
exemption, the conflict resolution

155
00:10:26,920 --> 00:10:31,940
logic in a format that, that is
human-readable and technology-independent.

156
00:10:32,440 --> 00:10:36,240
Think of it as a single source
of truth for what rule means,

157
00:10:36,440 --> 00:10:41,070
decoupled from how that rule will be
implemented in any particular system.

158
00:10:41,870 --> 00:10:44,730
The strategic advantage
of this is enormous.

159
00:10:44,810 --> 00:10:49,670
A single DSL model can generate
compliant code for a Java-based billing

160
00:10:49,670 --> 00:10:54,600
system, a Python microservice, and a
TypeScript front-end simultaneously

161
00:10:54,660 --> 00:10:57,180
without redundant development cycles.

162
00:10:58,150 --> 00:10:59,400
And because a DSL is a,

163
00:10:59,900 --> 00:11:01,560
a version control like source code,
every rule has a full audit history.

164
00:11:01,690 --> 00:11:07,220
You can always trace back, what did
this rule look like on January first?

165
00:11:07,520 --> 00:11:09,800
What changed on March fifteen, and why?

166
00:11:10,300 --> 00:11:14,670
Text to code engine is where the
TSL models are converted into a

167
00:11:14,670 --> 00:11:18,490
production-ready implementation
code This is done using a fine-tuned

168
00:11:18,490 --> 00:11:21,970
coding LLMs, the models that
have been specifically trained to

169
00:11:21,970 --> 00:11:26,350
understand the enterprise architecture
standard, target language convention,

170
00:11:26,530 --> 00:11:27,950
and system-specific constraint.

171
00:11:28,630 --> 00:11:33,380
The key architecture advantage, as I
mentioned, is that a single DSL rule model

172
00:11:33,480 --> 00:11:37,470
can generate a compliant code for multiple
systems and jurisdictions simultaneously.

173
00:11:38,140 --> 00:11:41,980
This eliminates what I call redundant
development cycle across subsidiary.

174
00:11:42,530 --> 00:11:46,600
The expensive error-prone process
where each regional engineering team

175
00:11:46,820 --> 00:11:48,980
re-implement the same rule independently.

176
00:11:49,690 --> 00:11:55,000
But, and this is critical, generated
